  {
    "client_msg_id": "babd76dc-1952-4ba3-a49c-cdf33338d493",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "&gt;  The resolution for move and paint commands introduces the possibility of *non-deterministic* behavior in games. For example, if a move-left and move-right command are sent to the same sprite, the resolution will choose one of the two commands at random. This is useful for coding unpredictable non-player character behavior.\nI like their approach to conflict resolution and that they explicitly state some commands can lead to non-determinism.  I actually think that for many game types determinism is overrated and their suggestion that you can exploit this as a feature (random selection of a move) is pretty cool.\n\nFacebook Horizon runs actions in order of execution (last action to change state will be the final state) but choosing a random command for immediate actions might have been a cool feature.  I also thought about introducing priority to actions",
    "user": "UBSMEUXAA",
    "ts": "1603496355.125300",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "user_profile": {
      "avatar_hash": "0edf98a60210",
